"Abstract As 1999 begins, the business world is bracing itself for an outburst of litigation with regard to the Year 2000 problem. Even taking the optimistic view that Year 2000 will not lead to an avalanche of cases in the Courts, it is increasingly clear that the growing complexity of IT projects, the increasingly tangled nature of contractual relationships and technology advances will all contribute to a growing number of IT disputes involving huge sums. Sad but true, it is still too often the rule (rather than the exception) that IT projects are delivered late and over budget. This article suggests some practical pointers to be borne in mind when negotiating IT contracts — although a good contract will help to avoid IT litigation, this will not always be possible and then a well-drafted contract can maximize the chances of success in any formal proceedings."
